	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Subsidies and small-scale fisheries: the development imperative and the sustainability challenge</h1>

			
			<h4>
												19 September 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> An informal round-table discussion on ‘Promoting development and sustainability in fishery subsidies disciplines’ was organised by UNEP in Geneva on June 30th 2005. The meeting provided a forum for an open discussion on issues of sustainable development in artisanal fisheries and more generally, options for S&amp;D treatment for developing countries, linking trade rules to sustainable development and poverty reduction.</p><p> Approaches to artisanal fisheries were the main focus of discussion, and specific consideration was given to how this sector can or should be protected within new WTO rules on subsidies. Attention was drawn to both the ‘developmental imperative’ and ‘sustainability challenge’ in terms of food security, poverty alleviation and the preservation in traditional lifestyles. The debate also explored the difficulties in finding a universal definition for artisanal fisheries.</p><p> Approaches to S&amp;D treatment for developing countries within the context of a new WTO subsidies regime were discussed in the light of making them operational and inclusive of sustainable development considerations. Participants identified the need for flexibility for developing countries to provide fisheries subsidies in the pursuit of their specific development priorities, subject to certain environmental and economic conditions. It was also highlighted that scientific and technical expertise outside of the WTO might be needed for ensuring sustainability of new S&amp;D disciplines.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Artisanal fishing: promoting poverty reduction and community development through new WTO rules on fisheries, prepared by D.K Schorr, June 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://www.unep.ch/etb/events/Events2005/midTermReview/AFPaperWorkDraft.pdf" target="_self">http://www.unep.ch/etb/events/Events2005/midTermReview/AFPaperWorkDraft.pdf</a> <br /> </p><p> ‘Reflecting sustainable development and S&amp;D treatment for developing countries in the context of new WTO fisheries subsidies rules’, working draft June 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://www.unep.ch/etb/events/Events2005/midTermReview/RefSustDevSDtre.pdf" target="_self">http://www.unep.ch/etb/events/Events2005/midTermReview/RefSustDevSDtre.pdf</a> <br /> </p><p> ‘Promoting development and sustainability in fishery subsidies disciplines’- Chair’s conclusions</p><p>

<a href="http://www.unep.ch/etb/events/2005rtGeneva.php" target="_self">http://www.unep.ch/etb/events/2005rtGeneva.php</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The need to define artisanal and small-scale fishing is becoming increasingly important to the fisheries subsidy debate. The Chair’s conclusions highlight that ‘both the development imperative and the sustainability challenge are very real in the artisanal sector.’ As such, artisanal fishers and small-scale fishing units should merit ASCM Article 27.1 recognition where ‘subsidies (may) play an important role in economic development’. But, whilst this may make defining artisanal and small-scale fisheries highly relevant, arriving at a ‘one size fits all’ definition of small-scale and artisanal fishing for LDCs and developing countries may prove counter-productive given the wide diversity displayed by the sector.</p><p> A two-pronged approach to the problem is therefore called for. On the one hand (as noted in the Chair’s report), a definition to be elaborated for the WTO could reflect the motives for subsidising the sector (such as poverty reduction, sustainable development, food security, and employment). On the other hand, it is possible to draw up some broad technical criteria, along the lines proposed by Brazil in their second submission to the WTO negotiating group on rules. In particular, that the fishing activities ‘are performed at an in-shore basis with non-automatic net-retriever devices’. Such a condition would automatically exclude the use of inappropriate and potentially destructive fishing technologies such as trawling and some purse-seine operations. Other qualifications proposed by Brazil that balance fishing for a livelihood and fishing for profits, could address the problem of the overcapacity and overfishing in the artisanal and small-scale fishing sector caused by inward investment by outside interests.</p>
		</div>
		
